SIMPLE: bile
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Bile
<hw>Bile</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>bilis</ets>:
cf. F. <ets>bile</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A
yellow, or greenish, viscid fluid, usually alkaline in reaction,
secreted by the liver. It passes into the intestines, where it aids in
the digestive process. Its characteristic constituents are the bile
salts, and coloring matters.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Bitterness of feeling; choler; anger; ill humor;
<as>as, to stir one's <ex>bile</ex></as>.</def>
<rj><au>Prescott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The ancients considered the bile to be the
⟦ldquo⟧humor⟦rdquo⟧ which caused irascibility.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Bile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Bile
<hw>Bile</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>byle</ets>, <ets>bule</ets>,
<ets>bele</ets>, AS. <ets>b⟦imac⟧le</ets>, <ets>b⟦imac⟧l</ets>; skin to
D. <ets>buil</ets>, G. <ets>beule</ets>, and Goth. <ets>ufbauljan</ets>
to puff up. Cf. <er>Boil</er> a tumor, <er>Bulge</er>.]</ety> <def>A
boil.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Bilection</ent>⟦br⟧
